--- !u!114 &896630867
MonoBehaviour:
  m_ObjectHideFlags: 0
  m_CorrespondingSourceObject: {fileID: 0}
  m_PrefabInstance: {fileID: 0}
  m_PrefabAsset: {fileID: 0}
  m_GameObject: {fileID: 896630866}
  m_Enabled: 1
  m_EditorHideFlags: 0
  m_Script: {fileID: 11500000, guid: 9541d86e2fd84c1d9990edf0852d74ab, type: 3}
  m_Name: 
  m_EditorClassIdentifier: 
  m_Material: {fileID: 0}
  m_Color: {r: 1, g: 1, b: 1, a: 1}
  m_RaycastTarget: 1
  m_RaycastPadding: {x: 0, y: 0, z: 0, w: 0}
  m_Maskable: 1
  m_OnCullStateChanged:
    m_PersistentCalls:
      m_Calls: []
  m_text: "Hey, howdy! Wow, all that for one and a half levels that play like a roblox
    game! Hell, I'm even ending it off with text on a wall like a shitty fnaf fan
    game. Hows that for vibes? \n\nI just wanted to put a few things, thanks for
    playing this shitty little proof of concept demo thing. This project has singlehandedly
    been my college education in game programming. \n\nHands and knees begging for
    feedback. I already know graphically it looks like shit. I mainly wanted to get
    this out to a playable state with showcases that each element is workable, sound,
    gameplay, animation, lighting, etc. But each part is iffy. So I'm mainly looking
    for feedback in three key areas: gameplay feel, level layout/design, and if there
    is potential in the first place. There's a very good reason indie devs typically
    stay away from 3D (except the lunatics at landfall and all that). So if this
    seems like a project that is genuinely too much to handle, aka I've sunk more
    time into it for the current outcome to have any merit. Then please be honest
    with me. I have other projects I can start up that aren't 3D and would be much
    more feasible. Thank you."
  m_isRightToLeft: 0
  m_fontAsset: {fileID: 11400000, guid: 8f586378b4e144a9851e7b34d9b748ee, type: 2}
